SIMPLE: expiation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Expiation
<hw>Ex`pi*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>expiatio</ets>: cf.F. <ets>expiation</ets>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of making satisfaction or atonement for any crime or fault;
the extinguishing of guilt by suffering or penalty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His liberality seemed to have something in it of self-abasement
and <qex>expiation</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The means by which reparation or atonement for
crimes or sins is made; an expiatory sacrifice or offering; an
atonement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those shadowy <qex>expiations</qex> weak,⟦br⟧
The blood of bulls and goats.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An act by which the threats of prodigies were
averted among the ancient heathen.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Hayward.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expiatist</ent>⟦br⟧
